            <h2>Frequently Asked Questions</h2>

            <div class="faq-item">
                <div class="faq-q">What are heart rate zones?</div>
                <div class="faq-a">Heart rate zones are ranges of heartbeats per minute that correspond to different exercise intensities. There are five zones, from Zone 1 (light warm-up at 50–60% of max heart rate) to Zone 5 (maximum effort at 90–100%). Training in different zones produces different physiological adaptations — lower zones build aerobic base and burn fat, while higher zones improve speed, power, and VO2max.</div>
            </div>

            <div class="faq-item">
                <div class="faq-q">How do I calculate my maximum heart rate?</div>
                <div class="faq-a">The most common formula is 220 minus your age. A more accurate formula developed by Tanaka et al. is 208 − (0.7 × age). For example, a 30-year-old would have an estimated max HR of 190 bpm (220−age) or 187 bpm (Tanaka). The only way to determine your true max HR is through a supervised maximal exercise test.</div>
            </div>

            <div class="faq-item">
                <div class="faq-q">What is the Karvonen method?</div>
                <div class="faq-a">The Karvonen method (also called Heart Rate Reserve method) uses your resting heart rate to calculate more personalized training zones. The formula is: Target HR = ((Max HR − Resting HR) × % intensity) + Resting HR. It produces higher zone thresholds than the standard method because it accounts for your fitness level through resting heart rate.</div>
            </div>

            <div class="faq-item">
                <div class="faq-q">Which heart rate zone burns the most fat?</div>
                <div class="faq-a">Zone 2 (60–70% of max HR) is commonly called the "fat-burning zone" because the highest percentage of calories burned comes from fat at this intensity. However, higher-intensity zones burn more total calories per minute. For overall fat loss, a mix of Zone 2 endurance work and higher-intensity intervals is most effective.</div>
            </div>

            <div class="faq-item">
                <div class="faq-q">How long should I train in each heart rate zone?</div>
                <div class="faq-a">General guidelines: Zone 1 for warm-up and cool-down (5–10 minutes). Zone 2 should make up 70–80% of your training volume — long steady sessions of 30–90 minutes. Zone 3 for tempo runs of 20–40 minutes. Zone 4 intervals of 2–8 minutes with equal rest. Zone 5 short bursts of 30 seconds to 2 minutes with full recovery. Most endurance athletes follow an 80/20 rule: 80% low intensity, 20% high intensity.</div>
            </div>

            <div class="faq-item">
                <div class="faq-q">What is a good resting heart rate?</div>
                <div class="faq-a">A normal resting heart rate for adults ranges from 60 to 100 bpm. Well-trained athletes may have resting heart rates as low as 40 bpm. Generally, a lower resting heart rate indicates better cardiovascular fitness. Factors that affect resting HR include fitness level, age, body size, medications, stress, and temperature.</div>
            </div>

            <div class="faq-item">
                <div class="faq-q">Is the 220-minus-age formula accurate?</div>
                <div class="faq-a">The 220-minus-age formula provides a rough estimate but has a standard deviation of about 10–12 bpm, meaning your actual max HR could be significantly higher or lower. The Tanaka formula (208 − 0.7 × age) is considered slightly more accurate based on a meta-analysis of 351 studies. For precise zones, a lab-based maximal exercise test is recommended.</div>
            </div>
